<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-366-872  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 366 872.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  July 1989 v7 n7 p172(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Arts andamp; Letters Graphics Editor. (Computer Support Corp.) (SoftwareReview) (one of five graphics software programs evaluated in'Well-rounded drawing') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Roth, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The reason to buy Arts andamp; Letters Graphics Editor is its massiveclip art library of symbols.andP;  Combine these with the aid of theprogram's Distribute tool to create complex drawings with noartistic talent required.andP;  But the drawbacks outweigh thebenefits.andP;  Curves must be drawn freehand; Arts andamp; Letters has nodirect curve-creation or auto-tracing tools.andP;  The user cannotcreate boxes or ovals using a tool; instead, they must be loadedfrom the symbol library by number.andP;  The indexed catalog makes iteasier, but on other programs it isn't necessary at all.andP;  Mistakescannot be 'undone,' but deletions can be cancelled.andP;  The program,from Computer Support Corp, costs $695, making it among the mostexpensive of graphics programs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Support Corp. (products).andO;Product:   Arts and Letters Graphics Editor (Computer graphics software).andO;Topic:     Graphics SoftwareEvaluation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Executive summary. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>